Chapter 3.5: Conditional Statements (if/else)

The ability to make decisions based on varying circumstances is 
fundamental to creating interactive and dynamic stories in Inform 6. 
This is where conditional statements, specifically the if and else 
constructs, come into play. These statements allow you to control the 
flow of your story by executing different code blocks depending on 
whether certain conditions are met.

The Basic Structure

The basic structure of an if statement in Inform 6 looks like this:

    if (condition) {
        // code to be executed if the condition is true
    }

Here, condition represents any expression that evaluates to either 
true or false. If the condition is true, the code block within the 
curly braces is executed. If the condition is false, the code block is 
skipped.

For example, the following code checks if the player is carrying a 
key:

    if (player carries key) {
        print "You unlock the door with the key.";
    }

In this case, if the player does indeed carry the key, the message 
"You unlock the door with the key." will be printed. If not, nothing 
will happen.

Adding Complexity with else

While the basic if statement is useful, it only allows for a single 
course of action when the condition is true. The else clause provides 
an alternative path to be taken when the condition is false.

Here's the structure of an if/else statement:

    if (condition) {
        // code to be executed if the condition is true
    }
    else {
        // code to be executed if the condition is false
    }

Let's expand on the previous example:
      
    if (player carries key) {
        print "You unlock the door with the key.";
    }
    else {
        print "You need a key to open this door.";
    }

Now, if the player doesn't have the key, they will be informed that 
they need one to open the door.

Nesting and Chaining Conditionals

You can further increase the complexity and flexibility of your 
decision-making by nesting if statements within other if or else 
blocks. This allows you to create a chain of conditions to be checked 
sequentially.

For example:

    if (player carries key) {
        if (door is locked) {
            print "You unlock the door with the key.";
            unlock the door;
        }
        else {
            print "The door is already unlocked.";
        }
    }
    else {
        print "You need a key to open this door.";
    }

In this example, the code first checks if the player has the key. If 
they do, it then checks if the door is locked. Only if both conditions 
are true will the door be unlocked.

Advanced Conditionals: else if and switch

Inform 6 offers additional tools for handling complex conditional 
logic:

    else if: This statement allows you to check multiple conditions 
    sequentially. If the initial if condition is false, the subsequent 
    else if conditions are evaluated one by one until a true condition 
    is found.

    if (player carries key) {
        // ...
    }
    else if (player has crowbar) {
        // ...
    }
    else {
        // ...
    }

    switch: This statement provides a more efficient way to handle 
    multiple conditions based on the value of a single expression. It 
    compares the expression's value to several potential matches and 
    executes the code associated with the matching case.

    switch (player's current location) {
        case Living Room:
            // ...
            break;
        case Kitchen:
            // ...
            break;
        default:
            // ...
    }

While if/else statements can achieve similar results, the switch 
statement can be clearer and more concise when dealing with numerous 
possibilities.

Important Considerations

Here are some important points to remember when working with 
conditional statements in Inform 6:

    Parentheses: The condition within an if statement must be enclosed 
    in parentheses.

    Curly Braces: The code block to be executed within an if or else 
    clause must be enclosed in curly braces, even if it's just a 
    single line.

    Indentation: While not mandatory, indenting the code within 
    conditional blocks significantly improves readability and helps 
    avoid errors.

    Boolean Expressions: Conditions in if statements typically involve 
    boolean expressions, which evaluate to either true or false. 
    Inform 6 provides various operators for constructing boolean 
    expressions, including comparisons (=, <, >), logical operators 
    (and, or, not), and checks for object properties or states.

By mastering conditional statements, you gain the power to craft 
intricate and responsive narratives in your Inform 6 games. With 
careful planning and thoughtful implementation, you can create stories 
that react dynamically to player choices and actions, leading to a 
truly immersive and engaging experience.

Chapter 3.6: Loops (for/while)

Loops are fundamental constructs in programming, allowing us to repeat 
a block of code multiple times. Inform 6 provides two primary loop 
structures: for loops and while loops. Additionally, it offers break 
and continue statements to control the flow of execution within loops. 
Mastering these tools is essential for crafting intricate and dynamic 
interactive fiction experiences.

The for Loop

The for loop is ideal for situations where the number of iterations is 
known beforehand. It iterates over a predefined sequence of values, 
executing the loop body for each value.

Syntax:

    for (initialization; condition; increment) {
      // loop body
    }

    initialization: This expression is executed once before the loop 
    begins. It typically initializes a counter variable.

    condition: This expression is evaluated before each iteration. If 
    it evaluates to true, the loop body is executed. If it evaluates 
    to false, the loop terminates.

    increment: This expression is executed after each iteration. It 
    typically updates the counter variable.

Example:

    for (i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
      print "Iteration number: ", i;
    }

This loop will print "Iteration number: 1", "Iteration number: 2", and 
so on, until "Iteration number: 5".

Nesting for Loops:

for loops can be nested within each other to create more complex 
iteration patterns. For example, the following code iterates over a 
two-dimensional grid:

    for (x = 1; x <= 5; x++) {
      for (y = 1; y <= 5; y++) {
        print "(", x, ",", y, ")";
      }
    }

Iterating over Collections:

While for loops are often used with numerical counters, they can also 
iterate over any collection of values. For example, to iterate over 
all the objects in a room:
      
    for (obj in Room) {
      print (obj.name);
    }

The while Loop

The while loop is used when the number of iterations is not known 
beforehand. It repeatedly executes the loop body as long as a specific 
condition remains true.

Syntax:

    while (condition) {
      // loop body
    }

    condition: This expression is evaluated before each iteration. If 
    it evaluates to true, the loop body is executed. If it evaluates 
    to false, the loop terminates.

Example:

    let i = 1;
    while (i <= 5) {
      print "Iteration number: ", i;
      increment i;
    }

This loop will print the same output as the first for loop example.

Choosing between for and while:

Use a for loop when the number of iterations is known beforehand and a 
while loop when the number of iterations is determined by a condition 
within the loop.

Loop Control Statements: break and continue

Inform 6 provides two statements to alter the flow of execution within loops:

    break: This statement immediately terminates the innermost loop, 
    regardless of whether the loop condition still holds.

    continue: This statement skips the remaining code in the current 
    iteration and jumps to the beginning of the next iteration, 
    re-evaluating the loop condition.

Example:
      
    for (i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
      if (i == 5) {
        break; // Terminate the loop when i reaches 5
      }
      if (i % 2 == 0) {
        continue; // Skip even numbers
      }
      print i;
    }

This code will print only the odd numbers from 1 to 4.

Using break and continue effectively:

While break and continue can be helpful in certain situations, overuse 
can make code less readable and harder to maintain. Consider 
alternative approaches, such as modifying loop conditions or using 
nested loops, before resorting to these statements.

Advanced Loop Techniques

Inform 6 offers additional features that can be used with loops to 
achieve more complex behavior:

    Loop labels: Loops can be labeled to allow break and continue 
    statements to target specific loops in nested scenarios.

    for loop variations: Inform 6 supports variations of the for loop 
    syntax, such as omitting the initialization or increment 
    expressions.

    while loop variations: The repeat ... until construct provides an 
    alternative syntax for while loops.

These advanced techniques can be useful in specific situations, but 
it's important to prioritize code clarity and maintainability when 
choosing the appropriate loop structure and control flow mechanisms.

Chapter 4: Functions and Procedures

Chapter 4.1: Defining and Calling Functions

Functions are self-contained blocks of code that perform specific 
tasks and can be called from different parts of your program. They 
promote code modularity, reusability, and organization, making your 
Inform 6 projects more efficient and maintainable.

This sub-chapter will provide a comprehensive exploration of defining 
and calling functions in Inform 6, covering their syntax, arguments, 
return values, scope, and considerations for effective function design 
and utilization within your interactive fiction games.

Defining Functions: Creating Reusable Code Blocks

The [ ... ] brackets are used to define functions in Inform 6. The 
basic syntax is:

    [ function_name arguments;
        code block
    ];

    function_name: The identifier used to call the function. Choose a 
    meaningful and consistent name that reflects the function's 
    purpose.

    arguments: A list of variables (separated by spaces) that the 
    function receives as input (optional). These arguments act as 
    placeholders for values that will be provided when the function is 
    called. Clearly define the expected data types of each argument.

    code block: The block of code enclosed within the brackets that 
    defines the function's behavior. This code block can contain any 
    valid Inform 6 statements and expressions.

For example, the following function calculates the area of a 
rectangle:

    [ CalculateArea width height;
        area = width * height;
        return area;
    ];

This function takes two arguments, width and height, calculates the area using the multiplication operator, and returns the result using the return statement.

Calling Functions: Executing Reusable Code

To call a function, use its name followed by a list of arguments (if 
any) enclosed within parentheses. For example:

    result = CalculateArea(5, 3);
    print "The area is: ", result;

This code calls the CalculateArea function with arguments 5 and 3, 
stores the returned value in the result variable, and then prints the 
area to the screen.

When calling a function, ensure that the number and data types of the 
arguments you provide match the function's definition. Arguments and 
Return Values: Data Input and Output

Functions can take arguments as input and return a single value as 
output.

    Arguments: When calling a function, you can provide values as 
    arguments, which are then assigned to the corresponding variables 
    declared in the function's definition. This allows the function to 
    operate on different data each time it is called.

    Return values: Functions can return a single value using the 
    return statement. This value can be a number, string, boolean, 
    object, or array. If no return statement is explicitly used, the 
    function returns the default value of true. The data type of the 
    returned value should be compatible with the variable or 
    expression where it is used.

Here's an example of a function with arguments and a return value:

    [ CheckInventory item;
        if (item in inventory) {
            return true;
        } else {
            return false;
        }
    ];

    if (CheckInventory(key)) {
        print "You have the key in your inventory.";
    }

The CheckInventory function takes an item as an argument and returns 
true if the item is found in the inventory, and false otherwise. The 
if statement then uses the returned boolean value to determine which 
message to print.

Scope of Variables within Functions: Local vs. Global

Variables declared within a function are local to that function and 
are not accessible outside its scope. This means that you can use the 
same variable names in different functions without conflicts.

However, functions can access and modify global variables declared 
outside of any function. Be mindful of potential side effects when 
modifying global variables within functions, as these changes can 
affect other parts of your code. If you need to modify global data 
within a function, consider using local variables or passing arguments 
by value to avoid unintended side effects.

Considerations for Effective Function Design

Here are some additional considerations for designing and using 
functions effectively in Inform 6:

    Modularity and reusability: Design functions to perform specific 
    tasks, promoting code reusability and reducing redundancy. This 
    makes your code more modular and easier to maintain.

    Naming conventions: Use meaningful and consistent names for 
