interactive fiction games.

Chapter 4.2: Passing Arguments and Returning Values

Functions in Inform 6 can be made more versatile and powerful by 
passing arguments and returning values. This allows you to create 
functions that can operate on different data and provide results that 
can be used in other parts of your code, promoting modularity and 
reusability.

This sub-chapter will provide a comprehensive exploration of passing 
arguments and returning values in Inform 6, covering their syntax, 
data types, considerations for effective usage, and advanced 
techniques for creating flexible and reusable functions within your 
interactive fiction projects.

Passing Arguments: Providing Input to Functions

When defining a function, you can specify a list of arguments that the 
function will receive as input. These arguments act as placeholders 
for values that will be provided when the function is called. For 
example:

    [ CalculateSum num1 num2;
        sum = num1 + num2;
        return sum;
    ];

This CalculateSum function takes two arguments, num1 and num2, which 
represent the numbers to be added. Choose meaningful and consistent 
names for your arguments to improve code readability and clarity.

When calling the function, you provide the actual values for these 
arguments:

    total = CalculateSum(5, 10);

In this example, the values 5 and 10 are passed as arguments to the 
function, and the function calculates their sum. Ensure that the 
number and data types of the arguments you provide match the 
function's definition to avoid errors and unexpected behavior.

Returning Values: Providing Output from Functions

The return statement is used within a function to specify the value 
that the function will return as output. This value can then be used 
in other parts of your code, allowing functions to communicate results 
and contribute to complex calculations or logic. For example:

    [ GetRandomNumber max_value;
        return random(max_value);
    ];

    random_number = GetRandomNumber(100);
    print "The random number is: ", random_number;

The GetRandomNumber function takes a max_value argument and returns a 
random number between 1 and max_value. The returned value is then 
