Chapter 4.3: Local and Global Variables

Variables in Inform 6 are categorized into two distinct types based on 
their scope and lifetime: local variables and global variables. 
Understanding the differences between these types is crucial for 
effective data management and code organization within your 
interactive fiction projects.

This sub-chapter will provide a comprehensive exploration of local and 
global variables in Inform 6, covering their definitions, scope, 
lifetime, usage scenarios, and considerations for ensuring data 
integrity and clarity within your code.

Local Variables: Temporary Data Storage within Routines

Local variables are declared within routines and are accessible only 
within that routine's scope. They are created when the routine is 
called and destroyed when the routine ends, making them ideal for 
storing temporary data used within a specific code block.

To declare local variables, list them on the opening line of a 
routine, separating them with spaces:

    [ CalculateArea width height area;
        area = width * height;
        ...
    ];

In this example, width, height, and area are local variables 
accessible only within the CalculateArea routine. They cannot be 
accessed or modified from other routines or outside the function's 
scope.

Using local variables for temporary data helps keep your code modular 
and prevents unintended side effects from modifying global variables. 
Choose meaningful and consistent names for local variables to improve 
code readability and maintainability.

Global Variables: Persistent Data Across Routines

Global variables are declared outside of routines and are accessible 
from anywhere in your code. They persist throughout the entire game 
session, making them suitable for storing data that needs to be shared 
and accessed across different routines.

Declare global variables using the Global directive, followed by the 
variable name and an optional initial value:

    Global score = 0;
    Global player_name;

In this example, score and player_name are global variables. score is 
initialized to 0, while player_name will have the default value of 0 
until explicitly assigned a value.

Use global variables sparingly and only when the data needs to be 
shared across different routines. Overusing global variables can lead 
to a cluttered namespace and make debugging more difficult. Choose 
meaningful and consistent names for global variables to improve code 
readability and avoid potential conflicts with local variables or 
other identifiers.

Considerations for Global Variables:

