Chapter 5: Worldbuilding and Object Interactions

Chapter 5.1: Creating Rooms and Objects

Rooms and objects form the core of the interactive world in Inform 6. 
Rooms represent locations that the player can visit and explore, while 
objects represent the entities that populate those locations and drive 
the narrative.

This sub-chapter will provide a comprehensive guide to creating rooms 
and objects in Inform 6, covering their definitions, attributes, 
properties, relationships, and considerations for building immersive 
and engaging game worlds.

Creating Rooms: Defining Locations

The Object directive is used to create rooms, even though they are not 
technically objects in the traditional sense. The basic syntax for 
defining a room is:

    Object room_name "Room Name"
    with
        description "Room description.",
        ...
    ;

    room_name: The identifier used to refer to the room within your 
    code. Choose a meaningful and consistent name that reflects the 
    room's location or purpose.

    "Room Name": The textual name of the room displayed to the player 
    (optional). This name should be descriptive and help the player 
    understand the nature of the room.

    description: A string or routine that provides a detailed and 
    evocative description of the room's appearance and contents. 
    Engage the player's senses and create a strong sense of atmosphere 
    through vivid language and sensory details.

    ...: Additional properties and attributes specific to the room, 
    such as map connections, light sources, and special behaviors.

For example:
  
    Object Library "Grand Library"
    with
        description "The library is vast and filled with towering 
        bookshelves. The scent of old leather and paper hangs heavy in 
        the air, and a hushed silence fills the room.",
        ...
    ;

This code defines a room named Library with the textual name "Grand 
Library" and a descriptive overview that engages the player's senses 
and establishes the atmosphere.

Creating Objects: Populating the World

Objects are also created using the Object directive. The basic syntax 
for defining an object is:
      
    Object object_name "Object Name"
    with
        name 'list' 'of' 'words',
        description "Object description.",
        ...
    ;

    object_name: The identifier used to refer to the object within 
    your code. Choose a name that clearly identifies the object and 
    its purpose.

    "Object Name": The textual name of the object displayed to the 
    player (optional). This name should be descriptive and help the 
    player understand what the object is.

    name: A list of dictionary words that can be used by the player to 
    refer to the object. Include synonyms and relevant keywords to 
    ensure that the parser can recognize the object from various 
    player inputs.

    description: A string or routine that provides a detailed and 
    informative description of the object's appearance and properties.

    ...: Additional properties and attributes specific to the object, 
    such as its initial location, whether it can be taken or 
    interacted with, and any special behaviors.

For example:

    Object -> book "leather-bound book"
    with
        name 'book' 'leather' 'bound',
        description "The book is old and its leather cover is worn. 
        The pages are filled with faded ink and intricate 
        illustrations.",
        ...
    ;

This code defines an object named book with the textual name 
"leather-bound book", a list of names, and a detailed description that 
provides information and evokes a sense of age and mystery. The -> 
indicates that the book is initially located in the previously defined 
room (in this case, the Library).

Attributes: Defining Object Characteristics

Attributes are boolean flags that define specific characteristics and
behaviors of objects. They are declared using the Attribute directive
and assigned to objects using the has keyword. For example:

    Attribute edible;

    Object -> apple "red apple"
    with
        ...
        has edible;

This code declares an edible attribute and assigns it to the apple
object, indicating that the apple can be eaten by the player.

The Inform 6 library provides a set of standard attributes, such as
container, supporter, openable, locked, and switchable, that define
common object behaviors. You can also create custom attributes to
implement unique mechanics in your game.

Properties: Storing Object Information

Properties are variables associated with objects that store
information about their state and attributes. They are declared within
the with segment of an object definition and accessed using the object
name and a dot notation. For example:

    Object -> lamp "brass lamp"
    with
        light_source true,
        ...
    ;

    if (lamp.light_source) {
        print "The lamp is providing light.";
    }

This code defines a lamp object with a light_source property that
indicates whether the lamp is currently emitting light.

You can define custom properties to store any information relevant to
your objects, such as weight, value, or specific states.

Relationships Between Rooms and Objects

Rooms and objects are interconnected within the game world:

    Containment: Objects can be contained within other objects or
    rooms. This is typically represented using the object tree, where
    child objects are considered to be inside their parent objects.

    Map connections: Rooms are connected to each other through exits,
    allowing the player to move between locations. These connections
    can be defined using direction properties like n_to, s_to, e_to,
    and w_to.

By understanding the principles of creating rooms and objects and 
applying these considerations for their definition and usage, you can 
build immersive and engaging game worlds in Inform 6, providing a rich 
and interactive experience for your players.

