Chapter 5.2: Defining Object Properties and Behaviors

Objects in Inform 6 are more than just static entities; they can have 
dynamic properties and behaviors that define how they interact with 
the player and the game world. This sub-chapter will provide a 
comprehensive exploration of defining object properties and behaviors 
in Inform 6, covering attributes, properties, routines, messages, and 
advanced techniques for creating interactive and engaging objects 
within your interactive fiction games.

Attributes: Flags for Object Characteristics

Attributes are boolean flags that define specific characteristics and 
behaviors of objects. They are declared using the Attribute directive 
and assigned to objects using the has keyword. For example:

Attribute edible;

    Object -> apple "red apple"
    with
        ...
        has edible;

This code declares an edible attribute and assigns it to the apple 
object, indicating that the apple can be eaten by the player.

The Inform 6 library provides a set of standard attributes that define 
common object behaviors:

    container: Indicates that the object can contain other objects.

    supporter: Indicates that other objects can be placed on top of 
    this object.

    openable: Indicates that the object can be opened and closed 
    (e.g., doors, containers).

    locked: Indicates that the object is currently locked and cannot 
    be opened.

    lockable: Indicates that the object can be locked and unlocked 
    with a key.

    switchable: Indicates that the object can be switched on and off 
    (e.g., lights, machines).

    on: Indicates that a switchable object is currently switched on.

    transparent: Indicates that the object is transparent and its 
    contents are visible.

    animate: Indicates that the object is alive (e.g., characters, 
    animals).

    talkable: Indicates that the object can be spoken to (e.g., 
    computers, robots).

    proper: Indicates that the object's name is a proper noun and 
    should not be preceded by an article.

    scenery: Indicates that the object is part of the scenery and 
    should not be listed in room descriptions or taken by the player.

    static: Indicates that the object is fixed in place and cannot be 
    moved.

    visited: Indicates that the player has visited this room.

    moved: Indicates that the object has been held by the player at 
    some point.

You can also create custom attributes to implement unique mechanics 
and behaviors specific to your game.

Properties: Storing Object Information

Properties are variables associated with objects that store 
information about their state and attributes. They are declared within 
the with segment of an object definition and accessed using the object 
name and a dot notation. For example:

    Object -> lamp "brass lamp"
    with
        light_source true,
        battery_power 100,
        ...
    ;

    if (lamp.light_source) {
        print "The lamp is providing light.";
    }

    lamp.battery_power = lamp.battery_power - 10;

This code defines a lamp object with light_source and battery_power 
properties. The code then checks if the lamp is providing light and 
decreases its battery power.

You can define custom properties to store any information relevant to 
your objects, such as weight, value, color, or specific states.

Routines: Defining Object Responses

Routines are code blocks associated with objects that define their 
responses to actions and events. They are declared within the object 
definition and can be triggered by messages sent from the Inform 6 
library or other objects.

Commonly used routines include:

    before: This routine is called before an action is performed on 
    the object. It can be used to block the action, modify its 
    behavior, or print custom messages.

    after: This routine is called after an action is performed on the 
    object. It can be used to react to the action, modify the game 
    state, or print custom messages.

    describe: This routine is called when the object needs to be 
    described in a room description. It can be used to provide a 
    dynamic description based on the object's current state.

    initial: This routine is called when the room containing the 
    object is first entered. It can be used to print an initial 
    description of the object or set up its initial state.

    each_turn: This routine is called at the end of every turn if the 
    object is in scope. It can be used to implement ongoing behaviors 
    or update the object's state.

Messages: Communication Between Objects

Objects can communicate with each other by sending messages. A message 
consists of a name and optional parameters. When an object receives a 
message, it looks for a corresponding routine with the same name. If 
the routine exists, it is executed with the provided parameters.

For example, you could define a Drink message that can be sent to 
objects representing beverages:

    Object -> potion "healing potion"
    with
        ...
        drink [;
            player.health = player.health + 20;
            remove self;
            print "You drink the potion and feel your health 
            improve.";
        ],
