Chapter 5.3: Object Relations and Containment

Objects in Inform 6 do not exist in isolation; they interact and 
relate to each other within the game world. Understanding these 
relationships and the concept of containment is crucial for building a 
cohesive, logical, and interactive interactive fiction experience.

This sub-chapter will provide a comprehensive exploration of object 
relations and containment in Inform 6, covering the object tree, 
containment hierarchy, visibility and scope, special relationships, 
and considerations for creating a well-structured and interactive game 
world.

The Object Tree: Representing Containment Relationships

Inform 6 uses a hierarchical structure known as the object tree to 
represent containment relationships between objects. Each object can 
have a parent object, child objects, and sibling objects:

    Parent object: The object that directly contains the current 
    object.

    Child objects: The objects directly contained within the current 
    object.

    Sibling objects: Objects that share the same parent as the current 
    object.

The object tree starts with a single root object, typically 
representing the game world or the initial location. All other objects 
are then placed within this tree, creating a nested structure that 
defines which objects are contained within others.

For example, consider the following object definitions:

    Object House "Old House";

    Object -> Room "Living Room";
    Object -> -> table "wooden table";
    Object -> -> -> book "dusty book";

This code creates the following object tree:

    House
      -> Room
          -> table
              -> book

In this example, the House object contains the Room object, which in 
turn contains the table object. The book object is ultimately 
contained within the House object, with table as its immediate parent.

Considerations for Object Tree Design:

    Logical structure: Create a logical and consistent object tree 
    that reflects the relationships between objects in your game 
    world. This will help you and your players understand how objects 
    are connected and interact with each other.

    Memory limitations: Be mindful of memory limitations when creating 
    complex object hierarchies or large numbers of objects. Consider 
    optimization techniques if necessary to ensure efficient memory 
    usage and avoid performance issues.

Containment Hierarchy and Visibility

The object tree not only defines containment but also influences 
visibility and scope:

    Visibility: Objects are generally visible to the player only if 
    they are in the same location or contained within a transparent 
    object. The object tree helps determine which objects are visible 
    based on their containment relationships. For example, an object 
    inside a closed box would not be visible to the player unless the 
    box is transparent.

    Scope: Scope refers to the set of objects that the player can 
    interact with at any given time. The object tree plays a role in 
    determining scope, as objects contained within other objects might 
    be outside the player's immediate scope. For example, the player 
    cannot directly interact with an object inside a locked container 
    unless they first open the container.

Considerations for Visibility and Scope:

    Use the transparent attribute and other techniques to control 
    which objects are visible and accessible to the player. This 
    allows you to create puzzles and challenges based on visibility 
    and object interactions.

    Be mindful of how containment affects scope and ensure that 
    objects are accessible to the player when needed for puzzles or 
    narrative progression.

Special Relationships: Beyond Containment

Inform 6 allows you to define additional relationships between objects 
beyond simple containment:

    Supporters: Objects with the supporter attribute can have other 
    objects placed on top of them. This relationship is distinct from 
    containment, as objects on top of a supporter are still considered 
    to be in the same location as the supporter. For example, a table 
    is a supporter, and objects can be placed on top of it.

    Doors: Objects with the door attribute act as connections between 
    rooms. They can be open or closed, locked or unlocked, and 
    influence the player's ability to move between locations. Doors 
    add interactivity and complexity to the game world, allowing you 
    to create puzzles and challenges based on access and navigation.

    Custom relationships: You can define custom relationships between 
    objects using properties and routines. For example, you could 
    create a "friend" property to track relationships between 
    characters or a "connected_to" property to define connections 
    between machines or devices. Custom relationships allow you to 
    implement unique game mechanics and narrative elements.

When defining custom relationships, ensure that their purpose and 
behavior are clearly documented and consistent within your game's 
logic.

By understanding the principles of object relations and containment 
and applying these considerations for their definition and usage, you 
can build well-structured and interactive game worlds in Inform 6, 
providing a logical and engaging experience for your players.

Chapter 5.4: Exits and Room Connections

Exits and room connections are fundamental elements in interactive 
fiction, allowing players to navigate and explore the game world. 
Inform 6 provides a flexible system for defining and managing these 
connections, enabling you to create intricate and engaging 
environments for your players to traverse.

This sub-chapter will offer a comprehensive exploration of exits and 
room connections in Inform 6, covering direction properties, doors, 
custom connections, and best practices for building well-structured 
and navigable game worlds.

Direction Properties: Defining Basic Connections

The most common way to define room connections is through direction 
properties. Inform 6 provides twelve standard direction properties:

    n_to (north)

    s_to (south)

    e_to (east)

    w_to (west)

    ne_to (northeast)

    nw_to (northwest)

    se_to (southeast)

    sw_to (southwest)

    u_to (up)

    d_to (down)

    in_to (in)

    out_to (out)

These properties are assigned values within room definitions to 
specify the connections to other rooms or objects. For example:

    Object LivingRoom "Living Room"
    with
        description "A cozy living room with a fireplace.",
        n_to Kitchen,
        e_to Garden,
    ;

This code defines a LivingRoom object with connections to the Kitchen 
object in the north and the Garden object in the east.

Doors: Creating Interactive Connections

Doors are special objects that act as interactive connections between 
rooms. They can be open or closed, locked or unlocked, and require the 
player to perform specific actions to pass through.

To define a door, you need to:

    Create an object with the door attribute.

    Set its door_to property to the room or object it leads to.

    Set its door_dir property to the corresponding direction property 
    (e.g., n_to).

    Set the appropriate direction property of the room containing the 
    door to the door object itself.

For example:

    Object -> FrontDoor "wooden door"
    with
        description "A sturdy wooden door.",
        door_to EntranceHall,
        door_dir s_to,
        has door openable;

    Object LivingRoom "Living Room"
    with
        ...
        s_to FrontDoor,
    ;

This code defines a FrontDoor object that connects the LivingRoom to 
the EntranceHall. The door is openable, meaning the player can open 
and close it.

Custom Connections: Beyond Standard Directions

While the standard direction properties are sufficient for most games, 
Inform 6 allows you to define custom connections using routines and 
properties. This enables you to create non-standard movement options, 
such as teleportation or travel through portals.

For example, you could define a teleport_to property that specifies a 
destination room:

    Object -> Portal "glowing portal"
    with
        teleport_to ThroneRoom,
        ...
    ;

    [ GoThroughPortal;
        if (noun == Portal) {
            move player to Portal.teleport_to;
            print "You step through the portal and find yourself in a 
            different room.";
        }
    ];

This code defines a Portal object with a teleport_to property. The 
GoThroughPortal routine handles the action of going through the 
portal, teleporting the player to the specified destination.

Special Exit Types: Adding Variety and Challenge

Beyond the standard exits that lead to other rooms, Inform 6 allows 
you to define special exit types that add variety and challenge to 
your game world:

    One-way exits: These exits only allow movement in one direction. 
    For example, a trapdoor might allow the player to go down but not 
    back up. You can implement one-way exits by setting the 
    appropriate direction property of the destination room to 0 or 
    nothing.

    Conditional exits: These exits only allow movement under certain 
    conditions. For example, a magical portal might only open if the 
    player possesses a specific item or has solved a puzzle. You can 
    implement conditional exits by using routines for the direction 
    properties or by defining custom messages and actions.

    Blocked exits: These exits are initially blocked and require the 
    player to perform an action to unblock them. For example, a door 
    might be blocked by rubble that needs to be cleared away. You can 
    implement blocked exits by using attributes or properties to track 
    the state of the exit and modifying the before routine of the Go 
    action to check for these conditions.

    Fake exits: These exits appear to be valid but lead nowhere or 
    have unexpected consequences. For example, a mirror might seem 
    like an exit but actually teleports the player to a different 
    location. You can implement fake exits by using routines for the 
    direction properties and customizing the behavior of the Go 
    action.

Best Practices and Considerations

Here are some best practices and considerations for defining exits and 
room connections in Inform 6:

    Clarity and consistency: Use meaningful names and comments to 
    improve the readability and maintainability of your code when 
    defining room connections.

    Logical structure: Create a map that is logically structured and 
    easy for players to navigate. Avoid overly complex or confusing 
