Chapter 6: Player Interaction and Input

Chapter 6.1: Parsing Player Commands

The heart of interactive fiction lies in the player's ability to 
interact with the game world through textual commands. The Inform 6 
parser plays a crucial role in this process, taking the player's input 
and translating it into actions that the game can understand and 
execute.

This sub-chapter will provide a comprehensive exploration of how 
Inform 6 parses player commands, covering the parsing process, 
grammar, tokenization, disambiguation, and advanced techniques for 
creating a robust and flexible system for interpreting player input.

The Parsing Process: From Text to Action

The Inform 6 parser follows a multi-step process to translate player 
commands into actions:

    Reading input: The parser reads the player's command from the 
    keyboard or an input stream.

    Tokenization: The parser breaks down the command into individual 
    words and punctuation marks, creating a stream of tokens.

    Identifying the actor: The parser looks for a comma to determine 
    if the command is addressed to a specific actor (e.g., "wizard, 
    cast spell"). If no comma is found, the player is assumed to be 
    the actor.

    Identifying the verb: The parser identifies the verb in the 
    command and looks up its associated grammar.

    Matching grammar: The parser attempts to match the remaining 
    tokens in the command to the grammar lines defined for the verb. 
    This process involves matching tokens to specific grammatical 
    elements like nouns, prepositions, and numbers.

    Disambiguation: If multiple objects or interpretations match the 
    player's input, the parser uses a set of rules and heuristics to 
    resolve the ambiguity and determine the intended action.

    Action generation: Once the parser has successfully matched the 
    command to a grammar line, it generates the corresponding action 
    with the appropriate actor, verb, noun, and second noun.

Grammar: Defining Valid Command Structures

Grammar in Inform 6 defines the valid ways in which verbs can be used 
in player commands. It is specified using the Verb and Extend 
directives, which create and modify grammar lines for verbs.

A grammar line consists of a sequence of tokens that represent the 
expected elements in a command. For example:

    Verb 'take' 'get' 'grab'
        * noun -> Take;

This grammar line for the Take verb specifies that the verb should be 
followed by a single noun, resulting in the Take action.

Inform 6 provides various built-in tokens, such as noun, held, multi, 
preposition, and number, that represent different grammatical 
elements. You can also define custom tokens using general parsing 
routines to handle more complex or language-specific syntax.

Tokenization: Breaking Down the Command

Tokenization is the process of breaking down the player's command into 
individual words and punctuation marks. The parser uses spaces and 
certain punctuation marks (e.g., commas, periods) as delimiters to 
identify tokens.

For example, the command "take the red key from the table" would be 
tokenized as follows:

    take / the / red / key / from / the / table

Each token is then processed according to the grammar rules defined 
for the verb.

Disambiguation: Resolving Ambiguities

When multiple objects or interpretations match the player's input, the 
parser needs to resolve the ambiguity and determine the intended 
action. Inform 6 uses a set of rules and heuristics for 
disambiguation, taking into account factors like:

    Definiteness: Whether the noun phrase is definite (e.g., "the 
    key") or indefinite (e.g., "a key").

    Scope: Which objects are currently visible and accessible to the 
    player.

    Pronouns: The referents of pronouns like "it" or "them" based on 
    the context.

    Object properties: Specific properties of objects, such as being 
    edible or wearable, can influence disambiguation in the context of 
    certain actions.

The parser might also ask clarifying questions to the player if the 
ambiguity cannot be resolved automatically.

Advanced Techniques: Customizing Parsing Behavior

Inform 6 offers several advanced techniques for customizing parsing 
behavior:

    parse_name property: You can define a parse_name routine for an 
    object to override the default name matching behavior and provide 
    more flexible recognition of object names.

    grammar property: You can define a grammar routine for animate or 
    talkable objects to specify custom grammars that are used when the 
    player addresses commands to these objects.

    BeforeParsing and UnknownVerb entry points: These routines allow 
    you to modify the parsing process at a low level, enabling you to 
    handle special cases or implement language-specific features.

By understanding the parsing process and utilizing these advanced 
techniques, you can create a robust and flexible system for 
interpreting player input, ensuring that your interactive fiction 
games can understand a wide range of commands and provide a natural 
and engaging experience for your players.

Chapter 6.2: Handling Different Verb Types

The Inform 6 parser recognizes various verb types, each with its own 
characteristics and implications for how player commands are 
interpreted and processed. Understanding these different verb types is 
crucial for creating a robust and flexible system for handling player 
input in your interactive fiction games.

This sub-chapter will provide a comprehensive exploration of different 
verb types in Inform 6, covering standard verbs, meta verbs, 
untypeable verbs, and best practices for defining and utilizing verbs 
effectively to create a natural and engaging interactive experience.

Standard Verbs: Actions in the Game World

Standard verbs represent actions that the player can perform within 
the game world, such as taking objects, moving between locations, 
examining items, and interacting with characters. They are defined 
using the Verb directive and have associated grammar lines that 
specify valid command structures.

For example, the following code defines a standard verb for examining 
objects:

    Verb 'examine' 'look at' 'inspect'
        * noun -> Examine;

This Examine verb allows the player to use commands like "examine 
book" or "look at sword", resulting in the Examine action being 
generated and processed by the game.

Meta Verbs: Actions Outside the Game World

Meta verbs represent actions that are not directly part of the game 
world but rather control the game itself or provide information to the 
player. Examples include verbs like "save", "restore", "score", and 
"quit".

Meta verbs are defined using the Verb meta directive and typically 
have simpler grammar than standard verbs. For example:

    Verb meta 'score' * -> Score;

This defines a meta verb Score that simply triggers the Score action, 
which displays the player's current score.

Meta verbs are not affected by the game state or world model rules, 
making them reliable for providing essential game control and 
information regardless of the player's current situation.

Untypeable Verbs: Hidden Commands and Special Cases

Untypeable verbs are a special type of verb that cannot be directly 
typed by the player. They are typically used for internal purposes or 
to implement hidden commands and special cases.

Untypeable verbs are defined using a verb word that includes 
punctuation, such as a comma or period. For example:

    Verb 'debug,' * noun -> DebugObject;

This defines an untypeable verb debug, that triggers the DebugObject 
action when used with a noun. However, the player cannot directly type 
"debug," as the parser will separate it into two words.

Untypeable verbs can be useful for:

    Internal actions: Defining actions that are only triggered by the 
    game's internal logic or by other objects sending messages.

    Hidden commands: Implementing secret or debug commands that are 
    not accessible through normal gameplay.

    Special grammar cases: Handling specific grammatical structures or 
    language features that cannot be easily parsed with standard 
    verbs.

Best Practices and Considerations

Here are some best practices and considerations for defining and 
utilizing verbs in Inform 6:

    Clarity and consistency: Use meaningful and consistent verb names 
    and synonyms to improve code readability and make commands 
    intuitive for players.

    Grammar design: Carefully design the grammar for your verbs to 
    ensure that they can handle the desired range of player commands 
    while avoiding ambiguity and parsing errors.

    Standard vs. meta verbs: Use standard verbs for actions that 
    interact with the game world and meta verbs for actions that 
    control the game or provide information.

    Untypeable verbs: Use untypeable verbs sparingly and only for 
    specific cases where they are necessary. Avoid relying on them for 
    core gameplay mechanics.

    Testing and debugging: Thoroughly test your verb definitions and 
    grammar to ensure that they parse player commands correctly and 
    generate the intended actions.

By understanding the different verb types and applying best practices 
for their definition and usage, you can create a robust and flexible 
system for handling player input in your Inform 6 projects, ensuring 
that your interactive fiction games are responsive, engaging, and 
enjoyable to play.

