Chapter 7: Rules and Events

Chapter 7.1: Defining and Triggering Rules

Rules are a powerful mechanism in Inform 6 that allow you to define 
dynamic and context-sensitive behavior within your interactive fiction 
games. They provide a way to specify actions or events that should 
occur when certain conditions are met, enabling you to create complex 
interactions and puzzles without explicitly coding every possible 
scenario.

This sub-chapter will offer a comprehensive exploration of defining 
and triggering rules in Inform 6, covering rule types, conditions, 
actions, triggering mechanisms, and best practices for using rules 
effectively to create dynamic and engaging gameplay experiences.

Rule Types: before, after, and instead

Inform 6 supports three main types of rules:

    before rules: Triggered before an action is performed. They can be 
    used to block the action, modify its behavior, or print custom 
    messages.

    after rules: Triggered after an action is performed. They can be 
    used to react to the action, modify the game state, or print 
    custom messages.

    instead rules: Replace the standard behavior of an action 
    entirely. They are less commonly used than before and after rules 
    but can be useful for implementing unique mechanics or overriding 
    default actions.

These rule types allow you to define specific responses and behaviors 
for objects and the game world based on the context and actions taken 
by the player.

Rule Conditions: Specifying When Rules Trigger

Each rule has a condition that determines when it should be triggered. 
The condition is a boolean expression that evaluates to either true or 
false. For example:

    after [;
        Take: if (noun == key) {
            print "You take the key. It feels cold and heavy in your hand.";
        }
    ];

This after rule for the Take action will only trigger if the noun 
involved in the action is the key object.

Rule conditions can be simple or complex, involving multiple 
comparisons, logical operators, and function calls. You can use any 
valid Inform 6 expression to construct a rule condition.

Rule Actions: Defining What Happens When Rules Trigger

When a rule's condition evaluates to true, the rule's action block is 
executed. This action block can contain any valid Inform 6 statements, 
including:

    Printing messages: Use print or print_ret to provide feedback to 
    the player or describe the results of the rule's actions.

    Modifying object states: Use give and take to change object 
    attributes or modify object properties.

    Moving objects: Use move and remove to move objects within the 
    object tree.

    Triggering events: Call functions or send messages to other 
    objects to trigger specific events or behaviors.

The actions within a rule can be as simple or complex as needed to 
implement the desired gameplay mechanics.

Defining Rules within Objects and Rooms

before, after, and instead rules are defined within objects and rooms. 
This allows you to associate specific rules with the entities they 
affect, creating a modular and organized structure for your game's 
logic.

    Object rules: Defined within the object's definition using the 
    before, after, and instead properties. These rules apply to 
    actions where the object is the noun (the primary object 
    involved).

    Room rules: Defined within the room's definition using the before 
    and after properties. These rules apply to actions that take place 
    within the room.

For example, the following code defines a before rule for the Take 
action on a key object:

    Object -> key "rusty key"
    with
        ...
        before [;
            Take: if (!player_has_permission) {
                print "You are not allowed to take the key.";
                rtrue;  ! Block the action
            }
        ],
        ...
    ;

This rule checks if the player has permission to take the key. If not, 
it prints a message and blocks the action.

Similarly, the following code defines an after rule for the Go action 
in a Forest room:

    Object Forest "Dark Forest"
    with
        ...
        after [;
            Go: if (random(10) == 1) {
                move monster to location;
                print "A monster suddenly appears!";
            }
        ],
        ...
    ;

This rule has a 10% chance of moving a monster into the room after the 
player enters.

By defining rules within objects and rooms, you can create a modular 
and organized structure for your game's logic, making it easier to 
understand, maintain, and extend your interactive fiction projects.

Triggering Mechanisms: How Rules Are Activated

Rules are typically triggered by actions performed by the player. When 
the player types a command, the parser generates an action, and the 
Inform 6 library then checks for any relevant rules associated with 
that action.

For before and after rules, the library checks the following:

    Object rules: The before and after properties of the noun object 
    involved in the action.

    Room rules: The before and after properties of the current room.

    Global rules: The GamePreRoutine and GamePostRoutine entry point 
    routines, which act as global before and after rules, 
    respectively.

For instead rules, the library only checks the instead property of the 
noun object.

If a rule's condition is met, its action block is executed, 
potentially modifying the behavior of the original action or replacing 
it entirely.

Best Practices and Considerations

Here are some best practices and considerations for defining and 
triggering rules in Inform 6:

    Clarity and conciseness: Keep your rule conditions and actions 
    clear and concise to improve readability and avoid potential 
    errors.

    Organization: Organize your rules logically within object and room 
    definitions. Use comments to explain the purpose and logic behind 
    each rule.

    Specificity: Define rules with specific conditions to avoid 
    unintended side effects and ensure that they trigger only when 
    desired.

    Efficiency: Consider the efficiency of your rules, especially when 
    using complex conditions or actions. Optimize your code where 
    necessary to avoid performance issues.

    Testing and debugging: Thoroughly test your rules to ensure that 
    they trigger correctly and produce the intended results. Use 
    debugging tools and techniques to identify and fix any issues.

By understanding the different rule types, conditions, actions, and 
triggering mechanisms, and by applying best practices for their 
definition and usage, you can leverage the power of rules to create 
dynamic and engaging gameplay experiences in your Inform 6 interactive 
fiction games.

Chapter 7.2: Rule Conditions and Actions

