Chapter 7.3: Event Handling and Responses

Events are occurrences within the game world that can trigger specific 
responses and behaviors. Inform 6 provides a robust system for event 
handling, allowing you to define how objects and the game world react 
to various events, creating a dynamic and interactive experience for 
your players.

This sub-chapter will offer a comprehensive exploration of event 
handling and responses in Inform 6, covering event types, response 
mechanisms, rule interactions, and best practices for creating a 
responsive and engaging game world.

Event Types: What Can Trigger Responses

Various types of events can trigger responses in Inform 6:

    Player actions: Actions performed by the player, such as taking an 
    object, moving to a new location, or interacting with a character, 
    are the most common events that trigger responses.

    Timed events: Timers and daemons can trigger events at specific 
    times or intervals, allowing for time-based puzzles, dynamic 
    changes in the game world, and background processes.

    Object interactions: Interactions between objects can also trigger 
    events. For example, dropping a fragile object might cause it to 
    break, or combining two objects might create a new object.

    Custom events: You can define custom events using messages and 
    routines, allowing you to trigger specific responses based on your 
    game's unique mechanics and narrative.

Response Mechanisms: How the Game Reacts

Inform 6 uses several mechanisms to respond to events:

    Rules: before, after, and instead rules associated with objects 
    and rooms define specific responses to actions and events based on 
    their conditions.

    Routines: Objects can have routines that are triggered by messages 
    sent from the Inform 6 library or other objects. These routines 
    can perform actions, modify the game state, or print messages in 
    response to events.

    Entry point routines: The Inform 6 library provides entry point 
    routines like NewRoom, TimePasses, and DeathMessage that allow you 
    to define global responses to specific events, such as entering a 
    new room or the passage of time.

These response mechanisms work together to create a dynamic and 
interactive game world that reacts to the player's actions and other 
events in a meaningful way.

Rule Interactions: Order and Precedence

When multiple rules are associated with an action or event, their 
order and precedence determine which rules take effect:

    before rules: Evaluated first, in the following order:

        GamePreRoutine (global before rule)

        orders property of the player object

        react_before properties of objects in scope

        before property of the current room

        before property of the noun object

    Action execution: If no before rule blocks the action, the action 
    is executed according to the standard game rules or a custom 
    action subroutine.

    after rules: Evaluated after the action is executed, in the 
    following order:

        react_after properties of objects in scope

        after property of the current room

        after property of the noun object

        GamePostRoutine (global after rule)

    instead rules: If an object has an instead rule for the action, it 
    replaces the standard action behavior entirely.

Understanding this order of evaluation is crucial for designing rules 
that interact with each other correctly and produce the desired 
outcomes.

Best Practices for Event Handling and Responses

Here are some best practices to keep in mind when designing event 
handling and responses in Inform 6:

    Clarity and organization: Keep your rules and routines 
    well-organized and easy to understand. Use comments to explain the 
    purpose and logic behind each response.

    Specificity: Define rules with specific conditions to avoid 
    unintended side effects and ensure that they trigger only when 
    desired.

    Efficiency: Consider the efficiency of your event handling, 
    especially for events that might occur frequently. Optimize your 
    code where necessary to avoid performance issues.

    Consistency: Maintain a consistent style and tone in your feedback 
    messages and responses throughout the game.

    Immersion: Consider how event responses can contribute to the 
    overall immersion of the game. Use descriptive language and 
    integrate responses into the narrative where appropriate.

    Testing and debugging: Thoroughly test your event handling and 
    responses to ensure that they function as intended and provide a 
    smooth and enjoyable experience for players.

By following these best practices, you can create a responsive and 
engaging game world in Inform 6, providing players with a dynamic and 
immersive interactive fiction experience.

Chapter 7.4: Using Rules for Complex Interactions and Puzzles

Rules are the backbone of complex interactions and puzzles in Inform 
6. They allow you to define dynamic behaviors and responses based on 
specific conditions, enabling you to create intricate and engaging 
challenges for your players without explicitly coding every possible 
scenario.

This sub-chapter will offer a comprehensive exploration of using rules 
for complex interactions and puzzles in Inform 6, covering rule 
combinations, event chains, puzzle design principles, and best 
practices for creating well-structured and satisfying puzzles that 
enhance the gameplay experience.

Combining Rules: Creating Intricate Interactions

By combining different rule types (before, after, and instead) and 
carefully crafting their conditions and actions, you can create 
intricate and dynamic interactions within your game world. Here are 
some examples:

    Conditional object behavior: An object's behavior can change based 
    on its state or the player's actions. For example, a lamp might 
    only be switchable if it has batteries, or a door might only open 
    if the player has the correct key.

    Chain reactions: One action can trigger a series of events. For 
    example, pulling a lever might open a door, which in turn triggers 
    a trap, and so on.

    Hidden consequences: Actions can have hidden or delayed 
    consequences. For example, taking an object might trigger a timer 
    that starts a countdown to an explosion.

    Complex puzzles: Rules can be used to create intricate puzzles 
    that require the player to combine objects, manipulate the 
    environment, and solve multiple steps in a specific order.

Event Chains: One Action Leading to Another

Rules can be used to create event chains where one action triggers 
another, leading to a series of events and consequences. For example:

    Object -> lever "rusty lever"
    with
        ...
        after [;
            Pull:
                give door open;
                print "The lever clicks and the door swings open.";
        ],
        ...
    ;

    Object -> door "heavy door"
    with
        ...
        before [;
            Open: if (!lever_pulled) {
                print "The door is stuck. You need to pull the lever first.";
                rtrue;
            }
        ],
        ...
    ;

In this example, pulling the lever triggers an after rule that opens 
the door. The door itself has a before rule that prevents it from 
being opened unless the lever has been pulled. This creates a chain of 
events where pulling the lever is necessary to open the door.

Puzzle Design Principles: Creating Satisfying Challenges

When using rules to create puzzles, keep the following design 
principles in mind:

    Clarity and logic: The puzzle's logic and solution should be clear 
    and understandable to the player. Avoid arbitrary or confusing 
    puzzles that rely on obscure solutions or guesswork.

    Clues and hints: Provide clues and hints within the game world to 
    guide the player towards the solution. These clues can be subtle 
    or explicit, depending on the difficulty of the puzzle.

    Fairness: Puzzles should be fair and solvable without resorting to 
    excessive trial and error or brute force. Avoid timed puzzles or 
    puzzles with random elements that can unfairly penalize the 
    player.

    Rewarding solutions: Solving a puzzle should be rewarding and 
    provide a sense of accomplishment. This can be achieved by 
    advancing the narrative, unlocking new areas, or providing the 
    player with useful items or information.

Best Practices for Using Rules in Complex Interactions and Puzzles

Here are some best practices to keep in mind when using rules for 
complex interactions and puzzles:

    Modularization: Break down complex interactions and puzzles into 
    smaller, manageable rules. This improves organization and makes it 
    easier to understand and debug your code.

    Comments and documentation: Use comments and documentation to 
    explain the purpose and logic behind your rules, especially for 
    complex puzzles or interactions.

    Testing and debugging: Thoroughly test your puzzles and 
    interactions to ensure that they function as intended and provide 
    a satisfying challenge for players. Use debugging tools and 
    techniques to identify and fix any issues.

    Balance: Balance the difficulty of your puzzles throughout the 
    game. Offer a mix of easy and challenging puzzles to keep players 
    engaged and motivated.

    Player experience: Consider the player's experience when designing 
    puzzles. Avoid frustrating or unfair puzzles that might lead to 
    player frustration or abandonment.

By following these best practices, you can leverage the power of rules 
to create complex interactions and puzzles that enhance the gameplay 
experience and provide your players with satisfying and memorable 
challenges within your Inform 6 interactive fiction games.

Chapter 8: Advanced Text Processing and Output

Chapter 8.1: Text Formatting and Manipulation

Inform 6 provides a range of tools and techniques for formatting and 
