Chapter 8.2: Dynamic Text Generation

Dynamic text generation allows you to create text that changes based 
on the game state, player actions, or other conditions. This enables 
you to craft interactive fiction experiences that feel more responsive 
and personalized to the player's choices and actions.

This sub-chapter will offer a comprehensive exploration of dynamic 
text generation in Inform 6, covering variable strings, printing 
routines, conditional text, and best practices for creating engaging 
and adaptive textual output in your interactive fiction games.

Variable Strings: Storing and Printing Dynamic Text

The string statement allows you to store text in variables, which can 
then be printed dynamically using the (string) printing rule. This 
enables you to change the text content based on game state or player 
actions. For example:

    string current_status;

    if (player_health > 50) {
        current_status = "You are feeling healthy.";
    } else {
        current_status = "You are injured and need to rest.";
    }

    print "Status: ", (string) current_status;

In this example, the current_status variable stores different text 
messages depending on the player's health. The print statement then 
dynamically prints the appropriate message.

Printing Routines: Customizing Text Formatting

You can define custom printing routines to format text in specific 
ways. These routines can take arguments and use conditional statements 
and loops to generate dynamic text output. For example:

    [ PrintInventoryList;
        print "You are carrying: ";
        if (children(player) == 0) {
            print "nothing.";
        } else {
            objectloop (obj in player) {
                print (name) obj, ", ";
            }
        }
    ];

    PrintInventoryList();

This PrintInventoryList routine dynamically generates a list of the 
player's inventory items, handling the case where the inventory is 
empty.

Conditional Text: Branching Narratives

Inform 6 allows you to create branching narratives where the text 
displayed to the player depends on specific conditions. You can 
achieve this using if/else statements within object descriptions, room 
descriptions, and printing routines. For example:

    Object -> door "wooden door"
