immersive and engaging experience for your players

Chapter 9.2: Saving and Restoring Games

The ability to save and restore games is a crucial feature in 
interactive fiction, allowing players to preserve their progress and 
resume their adventure at a later time. Inform 6 provides built-in 
mechanisms for saving and restoring game state, enabling you to create 
games that offer flexibility and convenience for your players.

This sub-chapter will offer a comprehensive exploration of saving and 
restoring games in Inform 6, covering the save and restore statements, 
save and restore entry points, handling save game data, best 
practices, and advanced techniques for creating a robust and 
user-friendly save system.

The save and restore Statements: Basic Save and Load Functionality

The save and restore statements are the core of Inform 6's save and 
restore system. They allow you to save the current game state to a 
file and restore it later.

    save statement: Saves the game state to a file with the specified 
    name. For example:

    save "my_game";

This code saves the game state to a file named "my_game".

    restore statement: Restores the game state from a file with the 
    specified name. For example:

    restore "my_game";

This code restores the game state from the file "my_game".

Save and Restore Entry Points: Customizing the Process

Inform 6 provides two entry point routines, Save and Restore, that 
allow you to perform additional actions or checks during the save and 
restore processes. These routines are optional, but they can be useful 
for:

    Saving additional data: You can use the Save routine to save data 
    that is not automatically saved by the save statement, such as 
    custom object properties or game state variables.

    Validating save files: You can use the Restore routine to validate 
    the save file and ensure that it is compatible with the current 
    version of your game.

    Performing actions on restore: You can use the Restore routine to 
    perform specific actions after the game state is restored, such as 
    updating the display or resetting timers.

Handling Save Game Data: Storing and Retrieving Information

When saving a game, Inform 6 stores the state of all global variables, 
object properties, and attributes. This data is written to a file in a 
specific format that can be read and interpreted by the restore 
statement.

You can also save additional data to the save file by using the Save 
entry point routine. This routine allows you to write custom data 
structures or information to the file, which can then be retrieved 
during the restore process.

Best Practices for Saving and Restoring Games

Here are some best practices to keep in mind when implementing save 
and restore functionality in Inform 6:

    Error handling: Implement error handling to gracefully handle 
    situations where the save or restore process fails, such as when 
    the disk is full or the save file is corrupted.

    Save game compatibility: Ensure that save files are compatible 
    with different versions of your game. If you make changes to the 
    game structure or data format, consider implementing a system for 
    migrating old save files to the new format.

    User interface: Provide a user-friendly interface for saving and 
    restoring games. Allow players to easily access their save files 
    and manage their saved games.

    Testing and debugging: Thoroughly test your save and restore 
    functionality to ensure that it works as intended and that players 
    can reliably save and resume their progress.

Advanced Techniques: Enhancing the Save System

Inform 6 offers several advanced techniques for enhancing your save 
system:

    Multiple save slots: Allow players to save multiple games in 
    different slots, providing them with the flexibility to manage 
    different playthroughs or storylines.

    Autosave: Implement an autosave feature to automatically save the 
    game at regular intervals or at specific points in the narrative.

    Save game compression: Use compression techniques to reduce the 
    size of save files, especially for large and complex games.

    Cloud save: Consider integrating with cloud storage services to 
    allow players to access their save files from different devices.

By leveraging these advanced techniques, you can create a robust and 
user-friendly save system that enhances the player experience and 
provides flexibility and convenience for your players.

Example

Here's an example of how to use the save and restore statements and 
the Save and Restore entry point routines:

    [ Initialise;
        ...
        if (restore_game) {
            restore "my_game";
        }
    ];

    [ Save;
        save "my_game";
        print "Game saved.";
    ];

    [ Restore;
        restore "my_game";
        print "Game restored.";
    ];

This code checks for a restore_game flag in the Initialise routine and 
restores the game if necessary. The Save and Restore routines handle 
saving and restoring the game state and provide feedback to the 
player.

Chapter 9.3: Flags and Switches

Flags and switches are essential tools in Inform 6 for tracking game 
state, controlling object behavior, and implementing complex 
interactions and puzzles. They allow you to store and manipulate 
boolean values (true/false) that represent various conditions and 
states within your game world.

This sub-chapter will offer a comprehensive exploration of flags and 
switches in Inform 6, covering their definitions, usage scenarios, 
differences between flags and attributes, and advanced techniques for 
leveraging these mechanisms to create dynamic and engaging gameplay 
experiences.

Flags: Global Variables for Tracking State

Flags are typically implemented as global variables that store boolean 
values. They are used to track various game states and conditions, 
such as:

    Player state: Whether the player is alive, dead, or has completed 
    a specific task.

    Object state: Whether a door is open or closed, a lamp is lit or 
