Chapter 10: Advanced Object-Oriented Programming

Chapter 10.1: Object Inheritance and Subclasses

Object-oriented programming (OOP) is a powerful paradigm that 
emphasizes code modularity, reusability, and organization. Inform 6 
incorporates key OOP principles through its class and object system, 
allowing you to create well-structured and efficient interactive 
fiction games.

This sub-chapter will provide a comprehensive exploration of object 
inheritance and subclasses in Inform 6, covering class definitions, 
inheritance hierarchies, overriding properties and routines, and 
advanced techniques for leveraging OOP principles to create a 
well-organized and maintainable codebase for your interactive fiction 
projects.

Class Definitions: Blueprints for Objects

Classes in Inform 6 act as blueprints for creating objects. They 
define common properties and behaviors that are shared by all objects 
belonging to that class. This promotes code reuse and consistency, as 
you can define properties and routines once in the class and have them 
inherited by all its instances.

The Class directive is used to define classes:

    Class Vehicle
    with
        name 'vehicle',
        speed 0,
        ...
    ;

This code defines a Vehicle class with a name property and a speed 
property.

Object Inheritance: Acquiring Properties and Behaviors

When you create an object and specify a class, the object inherits all 
the properties and routines defined in that class. For example:

    Object -> car "red car" Vehicle
    with
        ...
    ;

This code creates a car object that belongs to the Vehicle class. The 
car object automatically inherits the name and speed properties from 
the Vehicle class.

Inheritance allows you to avoid code duplication and create a 
hierarchical structure for your objects, organizing them based on 
their shared characteristics and behaviors.

Subclasses: Specialization and Refinement

Subclasses allow you to further specialize and refine the properties 
and behaviors of objects. A subclass inherits all the properties and 
routines from its parent class but can also define its own additional 
properties and routines or override inherited ones.

For example, you could define a Car subclass that inherits from the 
Vehicle class:
      
    Class Car Vehicle
    with
        num_wheels 4,
        ...
    ;

This Car subclass inherits the name and speed properties from Vehicle 
but also adds a num_wheels property specific to cars.

Subclasses allow you to create more specific and nuanced object types 
while still maintaining the benefits of code reuse and inheritance.

Overriding Properties and Routines: Customizing Inherited Behavior

Objects can override inherited properties and routines to provide 
customized behavior. For example:

    Object -> bicycle "blue bicycle" Vehicle
    with
        speed 10,  ! Overrides the default speed of 0 from Vehicle
        ...
    ;

In this example, the bicycle object inherits from the Vehicle class 
but overrides the speed property with a value of 10.

You can also override inherited routines by defining a routine with 
the same name within the object definition. This allows you to 
customize the behavior of specific objects while still leveraging the 
common functionality defined in the parent class.

Advanced Techniques: Leveraging OOP Principles

Inform 6 allows you to utilize advanced OOP principles to create more 
complex and flexible object structures:

    Multiple inheritance: Objects can inherit from multiple classes, 
    allowing them to combine properties and behaviors from different 
    classes. However, use multiple inheritance with caution, as it can 
    lead to complexity and potential conflicts if not managed 
    carefully.

    Polymorphism: You can define routines with the same name in 
    different classes, allowing objects of different types to respond 
    to the same message in different ways. This enables you to create 
    more dynamic and flexible interactions within your game world.

    Abstract classes: You can define abstract classes that cannot be 
    instantiated directly but serve as base classes for subclasses. 
    This allows you to enforce common interfaces and behaviors for 
    related subclasses.

By understanding and applying these advanced OOP principles, you can 
create sophisticated and well-structured object hierarchies in Inform 
6, enhancing the modularity, reusability, and maintainability of your 
interactive fiction projects.

Example

Here's an example of how to use object inheritance and subclasses to 
create a hierarchy of vehicles:

    Class Vehicle
    with
        name 'vehicle',
        speed 0,
        ...
    ;

Class Car Vehicle
    with
        num_wheels 4,
        ...
    ;

    Class Bicycle Vehicle
    with
        num_wheels 2,
        ...
    ;

    Object -> car "red car" Car
    with
        ...
    ;

    Object -> bicycle "blue bicycle" Bicycle
    with
        ...
    ;

This code defines a Vehicle class, a Car subclass, and a Bicycle 
subclass. The car and bicycle objects inherit properties from their 
respective classes and can also define their own specific properties 
and behaviors.

By carefully designing your class hierarchies and utilizing object 
inheritance effectively, you can create well-organized and efficient 
Inform 6 projects, making your interactive fiction games more scalable 
and maintainable.

Chapter 10.2: Polymorphism and Dynamic Binding

Polymorphism and dynamic binding are powerful object-oriented 
programming (OOP) concepts that enhance code flexibility and enable 
dynamic interactions within your Inform 6 projects.

This sub-chapter will provide a comprehensive exploration of 
polymorphism and dynamic binding in Inform 6, covering their 
definitions, implementation through message-passing, benefits, and 
advanced usage scenarios for creating a more dynamic and adaptable 
interactive fiction experience.

Polymorphism: Objects Responding Differently to the Same Message

Polymorphism, meaning "many forms," refers to the ability of objects 
belonging to different classes to respond differently to the same 
message. This allows you to write generic code that can operate on 
objects of various types without needing to know their specific class 
at compile time.

For example, consider a move routine defined in different classes:

    Class Animal
    with
        ...
        move [;
            print (name) self, " moves around.";
        ],
        ...
    ;

    Class Vehicle
    with
        ...
        move [;
            print (name) self, " drives forward.";
        ],
        ...
    ;

With polymorphism, you can write a generic function that sends the 
move message to any object:

    [ MoveObject obj;
        obj.move();
    ];

When MoveObject is called with an animal object, the move routine from 
the Animal class will be executed. When called with a vehicle object, 
the move routine from the Vehicle class will be executed. This dynamic 
behavior is possible due to polymorphism.

Dynamic Binding: Determining the Routine at Runtime

Dynamic binding is the mechanism that enables polymorphism. When a 
message is sent to an object, the Inform 6 runtime system determines 
the appropriate routine to execute based on the object's class. This 
binding of the message to the specific routine happens at runtime, 
allowing for dynamic and flexible behavior.

In the MoveObject example above, the decision of which move routine to 
call is made at runtime based on the type of object passed to the 
function. This is dynamic binding in action.

Benefits of Polymorphism and Dynamic Binding

Polymorphism and dynamic binding offer several benefits:

    Code flexibility and reusability: You can write generic code that 
    operates on objects of different types, promoting code reuse and 
    reducing redundancy.

    Dynamic interactions: Objects can respond to messages in different 
    ways based on their class, creating more dynamic and interactive 
    gameplay experiences.

    Extensibility: You can easily add new object types and behaviors 
    without modifying existing code, as long as the new objects 
    conform to the established interfaces (messages).

Advanced Usage Scenarios: Leveraging Polymorphism for Complex 
Interactions

Here are some advanced scenarios where polymorphism and dynamic 
binding can be particularly useful:

    Inventory management: You can define a generic use routine that 
    can be implemented differently for various objects, allowing the 
    player to use items in their inventory in context-specific ways.

    Character interactions: Characters can have different responses to 
    the same dialog choices or actions based on their personality, 
    relationship with the player, or current game state.

    Puzzle design: Polymorphism can be used to create puzzles where 
    objects need to be used in specific combinations or sequences, 
    regardless of their individual types.

    Custom game mechanics: You can implement unique game mechanics and 
    interactions by defining custom messages and routines that are 
    handled differently by different object types.

By carefully designing your object hierarchies and leveraging 
polymorphism and dynamic binding, you can create Inform 6 games that 
are more dynamic, flexible, and extensible, enhancing the overall 
gameplay experience and allowing for complex and engaging interactions 
within your interactive fiction worlds.

Example

Here's an example of how to use polymorphism to create a generic use 
routine for inventory items:

    Class Item
    with
        ...
        use [;
            print "You can't use that.";
        ],
        ...
    ;

    Object -> key "rusty key" Item
    with
        ...
        use [;
            if (door.locked) {
                door.locked = false;
                print "You unlock the door with the key.";
            } else {
                print "The door is already unlocked.";
            }
        ],
        ...
    ;

    Object -> potion "healing potion" Item
    with
        ...
        use [;
            player.health = player.health + 20;
            remove self;
            print "You drink the potion and feel your health improve.";
        ],
        ...
    ;

In this example, the Item class defines a default use routine that 
prints a generic message. The key and potion objects, both inheriting 
from Item, override the use routine to provide their specific 
functionality. This allows the player to use the "use" command on 
different items in their inventory, and the game will respond 
appropriately based on the item's type.

By leveraging polymorphism and dynamic binding, you can create more 
flexible and interactive gameplay experiences in your Inform 6 
projects.

Chapter 10.3: Defining Custom Object Behaviors

Inform 6 provides a powerful and flexible system for defining custom 
object behaviors, allowing you to create unique and interactive 
elements that enhance the gameplay experience and bring your 
interactive fiction worlds to life.

This sub-chapter will offer a comprehensive exploration of defining 
custom object behaviors in Inform 6, covering attributes, properties, 
routines, messages, inheritance, and advanced techniques for crafting 
objects that respond to player actions and interact with the game 
world in engaging and dynamic ways.

Attributes: Flags for Unique Characteristics

Custom attributes allow you to define unique characteristics and 
behaviors for your objects beyond the standard attributes provided by 
the Inform 6 library. You can use custom attributes to track object 
states, control interactions, and implement special game mechanics.

For example, you could define a flammable attribute to indicate that 
an object can be set on fire:

    Attribute flammable;

    Object -> torch "burning torch"
    with
        ...
        has flammable;

This flammable attribute can then be used in rules and routines to 
define how the object interacts with other objects and the game world. 
For instance, you could have a rule that states if a flammable object 
is in the same location as a fire source, it will catch fire.

When defining custom attributes, ensure that their purpose and 
behavior are clearly documented and consistent within your game's 
logic.

Properties: Storing Custom Object Information

Custom properties allow you to store and manage information that is 
specific to individual objects. You can use properties to track object 
states, attributes, relationships, and any other data relevant to your 
game's mechanics and narrative.

For example, you could define a color property for objects:

    Object -> ball "red ball"
    with
        color "red",
        ...
    ;

This color property can then be used in object descriptions, rules, 
and routines to dynamically describe the object or control its 
behavior based on its color.

When defining custom properties, choose meaningful and consistent 
names and document their purpose and usage to improve code readability 
and maintainability.

Routines: Defining Object-Specific Actions and Responses

Routines are code blocks associated with objects that define their 
responses to actions and events. You can define custom routines to 
implement unique behaviors and interactions for your objects.

For example, you could define a drink routine for a potion object:
      
    Object -> potion "healing potion"
    with
        ...
        drink [;
            player.health = player.health + 20;
            remove self;
            print "You drink the potion and feel your health improve.";
        ],
        ...
    ;

This drink routine increases the player's health, removes the potion 
from the game, and provides feedback to the player.

When defining custom routines, consider the following:

    Clarity and conciseness: Keep your routines clear and concise to 
    improve readability and avoid potential errors.

    Modularity: Break down complex behaviors into smaller, 
    well-defined routines.

    Error checking: Implement error checking to handle invalid input 
    or unexpected conditions gracefully.

    Comments and documentation: Use comments and documentation to 
    explain the purpose and behavior of your routines.

Messages: Communication and Interaction Between Objects

Custom messages allow objects to communicate and interact with each 
other in unique ways. You can define custom messages and corresponding 
routines to implement specific object interactions and behaviors.

For example, you could define a combine message that allows objects to 
be combined with each other:
      
    Object -> rope "sturdy rope"
    with
        ...
        combine [ other_object;
            if (other_object == hook) {
                create combined_object "rope and hook";
                move combined_object to player;
                remove self;
                remove other_object;
                print "You combine the rope and the hook.";
            } else {
                print "You can't combine those objects.";
            }
        ],
        ...
    ;

This combine routine checks if the other object is a hook. If so, it 
creates a new combined_object, moves it to the player's inventory, and 
removes the original objects.

Custom messages and routines allow you to create complex and dynamic 
interactions between objects, enhancing the interactivity and depth of 
your game world.

Inheritance: Leveraging Class Hierarchies

Inheritance allows you to define common behaviors and properties in 
classes and have them inherited by subclasses and individual objects. 
This promotes code reuse, consistency, and organization.

When defining custom object behaviors, consider using inheritance to 
create a hierarchy of objects with shared characteristics and 
behaviors. This can simplify your code and make it easier to manage 
and extend your game world.

Advanced Techniques: Creating Sophisticated Behaviors

Inform 6 offers several advanced techniques for defining sophisticated 
object behaviors:

    Dynamic properties and routines: You can modify properties and 
    routines during gameplay to create objects that change their 
    behavior or adapt to different situations.

    Recursion: You can use recursion within object routines to handle 
    hierarchical structures or complex interactions.

    Assembly language: For fine-grained control and optimization, you 
    can use assembly language within object routines to access 
    low-level Z-machine features.

By understanding and applying these advanced techniques, you can 
create objects with complex and dynamic behaviors that enhance the 
interactivity and depth of your interactive fiction games.

Example

Here's an example of how to use custom attributes, properties, 
routines, and messages to create a magic wand object with unique 
behaviors:

    Attribute magical;

    Object -> wand "wooden wand"
    with
        name 'wand' 'wooden',
        description "A simple wooden wand.",
        mana 100,
        cast_spell [ spell_name;
            if (self.mana >= spell_cost) {
                self.mana = self.mana - spell_cost;
                print "You cast the ", spell_name, " spell.";
                ...  ! Implement spell effects
            } else {
                print "You don't have enough mana to cast that spell.";
            }
        ],
        has magical;

This code defines a magical attribute and assigns it to the wand 
object. The wand also has a mana property to track its magical energy 
and a cast_spell routine that allows the player to cast spells using 
the wand.

By combining these elements, you can create a wand object that behaves 
differently from other objects in the game and allows for unique 
interactions and gameplay possibilities.

By carefully designing and implementing custom object behaviors, you 
can create a rich and interactive experience for your players, making 
your Inform 6 interactive fiction games stand out with their unique 
and engaging gameplay elements.

Chapter 10.4: Using Prototypes and Extensions

Prototypes and extensions are powerful tools in Inform 6 that allow 
you to further customize and extend the functionality of your 
interactive fiction games. Prototypes provide a way to define reusable 
object templates, while extensions offer pre-built libraries and 
modules that add new features and capabilities to your game.

This sub-chapter will offer a comprehensive exploration of using 
prototypes and extensions in Inform 6, covering prototype definitions, 
extending existing objects, creating and using extensions, and best 
practices for leveraging these mechanisms to enhance the functionality 
and complexity of your interactive fiction projects.

Prototypes: Reusable Object Templates

Prototypes are object definitions that act as templates for creating 
multiple similar objects. They allow you to define common properties 
and behaviors once and then easily create instances of the prototype 
with slight variations.

The Object directive with the prototype keyword is used to define 
prototypes:

    Object prototype Book
    with
        name 'book',
        description "A book.",
        ...
    ;

This code defines a Book prototype with basic properties and behaviors 
shared by all books.

To create an instance of a prototype, use the create message:

Object -> my_book = Book.create("The Adventures of Sherlock Holmes");

This code creates a new object my_book based on the Book prototype and 
sets its textual name to "The Adventures of Sherlock Holmes".

Prototypes are particularly useful for creating multiple objects with 
similar characteristics, such as books, weapons, or characters. They 
promote code reuse and consistency, reducing redundancy and making 
your code more maintainable.

When defining prototypes, consider the following:

    Common properties and behaviors: Identify the common properties 
    and behaviors that should be shared by all instances of the 
    prototype.

    Customization options: Consider how instances of the prototype 
    might differ and provide properties or routines that allow for 
    customization.

    Naming conventions: Use clear and consistent naming conventions 
    for prototypes and their properties and routines.

Extending Existing Objects: Adding Functionality without Modification

Inform 6 allows you to extend existing objects with additional 
properties and routines without directly modifying their original 
definitions. This is achieved through the Extend directive:

    Extend book
    with
        author "Unknown";

This code extends the book object (created earlier) with an author 
property.

Extending objects can be useful for:

    Adding new features: You can add new properties and routines to 
    existing objects to enhance their functionality or introduce new 
    gameplay elements.

    Customizing behavior: You can override inherited properties and 
    routines to customize the behavior of specific objects without 
    affecting other instances of the same class or prototype.

    Modularity: Extending objects allows you to keep your code modular 
    and organized, separating additional functionality from the core 
    object definitions.

When extending objects, ensure that the added properties and routines 
are consistent with the object's original purpose and behavior. 
Document the changes clearly to maintain code readability and avoid 
confusion.

Creating and Using Extensions: Expanding Game Capabilities

Extensions are pre-built libraries or modules that add new features 
and capabilities to your Inform 6 games. They can provide 
functionality such as:

    Menus and user interfaces: Extensions can provide pre-built menu 
    systems and user interfaces, saving you time and effort in 
    creating your own.

    Advanced text formatting: Extensions can offer advanced text 
    formatting options, such as color, custom fonts, and special 
    effects.

    Gameplay mechanics: Extensions can implement specific gameplay 
    mechanics, such as combat systems, inventory management, or puzzle 
    elements.

    World model extensions: Extensions can extend the Inform 6 world 
    model with new object types, attributes, and behaviors.

To use an extension, you typically need to:

    Download and install the extension files.

    Include the extension's header file in your source code using the 
    Include directive.

    Use the functions, routines, and objects provided by the extension 
    in your game code.

When choosing and using extensions, consider the following:

    Compatibility: Ensure that the extension is compatible with your 
    version of Inform 6 and any other extensions you are using.

    Documentation: Choose extensions with clear and comprehensive 
    documentation that explains how to use their features and 
    integrate them into your game.

    Modularity: Use extensions to add specific functionality without 
    bloating your core game code, maintaining a clean and organized 
    codebase.

Example

Here's an example of how to use prototypes and extensions to create a 
game with a menu system and custom object behaviors:

    ! Include the "Menus.h" extension
    Include "Menus";

    ! Define a prototype for menu options
    Object prototype MenuOption
    with
        name 'option',
        description "A menu option.",
        select [;
            ...  ! Implement option-specific behavior
        ],
        ...
    ;

    ! Create a menu object and add options
    Object MainMenu "Main Menu";

    Object -> StartGame = MenuOption.create("Start a new game");
    Object -> LoadGame = MenuOption.create("Load a saved game");
    ...

    ! Display the menu
    MainMenu.select();

This code includes the "Menus.h" extension to provide a menu system. 
It then defines a MenuOption prototype and uses it to create options 
for the MainMenu object. Finally, the select message is sent to the 
MainMenu to display the menu to the player.

By leveraging prototypes and extensions effectively, you can 
significantly enhance the functionality and complexity of your Inform 
6 projects, allowing you to create richer and more engaging 
interactive fiction experiences for your players.

Chapter 11: Debugging and Testing

Chapter 11.1: Identifying and Fixing Errors

Debugging is an essential part of the Inform 6 development process. 
Identifying and fixing errors in your code is crucial for creating 
games that function as intended and provide a smooth and enjoyable 
experience for your players.

This sub-chapter will offer a comprehensive exploration of identifying 
and fixing errors in Inform 6, covering error types, debugging tools 
and techniques, strategies for effective debugging, and tips for 
preventing errors in the first place.

Error Types: Understanding What Can Go Wrong

Inform 6 can encounter different types of errors:

    Compile-time errors: These errors are detected by the compiler 
    during the compilation process. They typically indicate syntax 
    errors, invalid data types, or other issues that prevent the code 
    from being compiled into a playable game file.

    Runtime errors: These errors occur during gameplay, often causing 
    the game to crash or behave unexpectedly. They can be caused by 
    various factors, such as accessing invalid data, attempting 
    impossible actions, or encountering logical inconsistencies in 
    your code.

    Logic errors: These errors do not cause the game to crash but 
    result in incorrect or unintended behavior. They can be difficult 
    to detect, as the game might appear to be functioning normally on 
    the surface.

Debugging Tools and Techniques: Finding the Culprits

Inform 6 provides several tools and techniques to help you identify 
and fix errors:

    Compiler error messages: The compiler provides detailed error 
    messages that indicate the type of error and its location in your 
    source code. Carefully read and analyze these messages to 
    understand the cause of the error and pinpoint its source.

    Debugging verbs: The Inform 6 library includes debugging verbs 
    like showobj, tree, showverb, and scope that allow you to inspect 
    the state of objects, the object tree, verb definitions, and scope 
    during gameplay. These verbs can be invaluable for understanding 
    the internal state of your game and identifying where things might 
    be going wrong.

    Tracing: You can enable tracing for actions, messages, timers, and 
    changes to track the execution of your code and pinpoint where 
    errors or unexpected behaviors occur.

    Infix debugger: The Infix debugger (available with the -X switch) 
    provides a powerful set of tools for inspecting and manipulating 
    the game state, calling routines, and evaluating expressions 
    during gameplay.

    Print statements: Adding print statements to your code can help 
    you track the values of variables and the flow of execution, 
    aiding in identifying logical errors or unexpected behavior.

Strategies for Effective Debugging: A Systematic Approach

Debugging can be a challenging process, but a systematic approach can 
help you identify and fix errors efficiently:

    Reproduce the error: Try to reproduce the error consistently. This 
    will help you isolate the specific conditions that trigger the 
    error and narrow down its source.

    Analyze error messages: Carefully read and analyze compiler error 
    messages and runtime error messages to understand the cause of the 
    error and its location in your code.

    Use debugging tools: Utilize debugging verbs, tracing, and the 
    Infix debugger to inspect the game state and track the execution 
    of your code.

    Divide and conquer: Break down complex sections of code into 
    smaller, more manageable chunks and test them individually to 
    isolate the source of the error.

    Test incrementally: Make small changes to your code and test 
    frequently to catch errors early and prevent them from 
    accumulating.

    Take breaks: Debugging can be mentally taxing. Take breaks when 
    needed to return to the problem with a fresh perspective.

Preventing Errors: Proactive Strategies

While debugging is essential, preventing errors in the first place can 
save you time and effort. Here are some tips for writing 
error-resistant Inform 6 code:

    Clarity and conciseness: Write clear and concise code that is easy 
    to understand and maintain. Avoid overly complex expressions or 
    convoluted logic.

    Naming conventions: Use meaningful and consistent names for 
    objects, routines, and variables to improve code readability and 
    reduce the likelihood of errors.

    Data types: Be mindful of data types and ensure that you are using 
    them correctly. Type mismatches can lead to unexpected behavior 
    and runtime errors.

    Error checking: Implement error checking in your code to validate 
    input, check for invalid values, and handle potential errors 
    gracefully.

    Testing: Test your code frequently and thoroughly, covering 
    different scenarios and edge cases to catch errors early.

By adopting these proactive strategies, you can write more robust and 
error-resistant Inform 6 code, reducing the time spent on debugging 
and creating a smoother and more enjoyable experience for your 
players.

Chapter 11.2: Using Debugging Tools and Techniques

Inform 6 provides a variety of debugging tools and techniques to help 
you identify and fix errors in your code. This sub-chapter will offer 
a comprehensive exploration of these tools and techniques, covering 
compiler error messages, debugging verbs, tracing, the Infix debugger, 
and advanced debugging strategies for tackling complex issues and 
ensuring the quality and stability of your interactive fiction games.

Compiler Error Messages: Understanding the Compiler's Feedback

The Inform 6 compiler provides detailed error messages when it 
encounters issues in your source code. These messages indicate the 
type of error, its location, and often provide hints or suggestions 
for fixing the problem.

When you encounter a compiler error, carefully read and analyze the 
error message. Pay attention to the following:

    Error type: The message will usually state the type of error, such 
    as "syntax error" or "undefined variable." This helps you 
    understand the nature of the problem.

    Location: The message will indicate the line number and file where 
    the error occurred. This helps you pinpoint the source of the 
    error in your code.

    Hints and suggestions: Some error messages provide hints or 
    suggestions for fixing the problem. These can be helpful starting 
    points for your debugging process.

If you are unsure about the meaning of an error message, consult the 
Inform 6 documentation or seek help from the Inform 6 community.

Debugging Verbs: Inspecting the Game State

The Inform 6 library includes several debugging verbs that allow you 
to inspect the state of your game during gameplay. These verbs can be 
invaluable for understanding the internal state of your game and 
identifying where things might be going wrong.

Here are some of the most commonly used debugging verbs:

    showobj: Displays detailed information about an object, including 
    its attributes, properties, and location in the object tree.

    tree: Prints the object tree, showing the containment 
    relationships between objects.

    showverb: Prints the grammar definition for a specific verb.

    scope: Lists all objects currently in scope, which are the objects 
    that the player can interact with at any given time.

Use these debugging verbs to inspect the state of objects, verify 
object relationships, and check the grammar definitions for your 
verbs. This information can help you identify inconsistencies or 
errors in your code.

Tracing: Tracking Code Execution

Tracing allows you to track the execution of your code by printing 
messages whenever specific events occur. You can enable tracing for 
actions, messages, timers, and changes using the following debugging 
verbs:

    actions: Prints a message whenever an action is generated, showing 
    the actor, verb, noun, and second noun involved.

    messages: Prints a message whenever a message is sent between 
    objects, showing the sender, receiver, message name, and 
    parameters.

    timers: Prints the state of all active timers and daemons at the 
    end of each turn.

    changes: Prints a message whenever an object is moved, or an 
    attribute or property state is changed.

Tracing can be helpful for understanding the flow of execution in your 
code and pinpointing where errors or unexpected behaviors occur. 
However, keep in mind that tracing can generate a lot of output, so 
it's best to use it selectively and focus on specific areas of your 
code where you suspect issues.

Infix Debugger: Powerful Runtime Manipulation

The Infix debugger provides a powerful set of tools for debugging your 
game at runtime. It allows you to:

    Evaluate expressions: You can evaluate any Inform 6 expression and 
    print its value. This is useful for checking the state of 
    variables, object properties, and function calls.

    Call routines: You can call any routine in your game directly, 
    allowing you to test specific functions or trigger events 
    manually.

    Send messages: You can send messages to objects, triggering their 
    corresponding routines and simulating player actions or object 
    interactions.

    Modify game state: You can modify the game state directly by 
    changing object attributes, properties, and locations. This allows 
    you to test different scenarios and bypass puzzles or obstacles 
    during debugging.

The Infix debugger is a powerful tool, but it should be used with 
caution. Modifying the game state directly can lead to inconsistencies 
or unexpected behavior. It's best to use the Infix debugger to inspect 
the game state and test specific functions or interactions rather than 
relying on it to bypass puzzles or alter the game flow significantly.

Advanced Debugging Strategies: Tackling Complex Issues

When dealing with complex errors or unexpected behaviors, consider the 
following advanced debugging strategies:

    Divide and conquer: Break down complex sections of code into 
    smaller, more manageable chunks and test them individually to 
    isolate the source of the error.

    Binary search: If you have a large section of code that is causing 
    problems, use a binary search approach to narrow down the 
    problematic area. Comment out half of the code and test. If the 
    error persists, the problem is in the remaining half. Continue 
    this process until you isolate the specific lines of code causing 
    the issue.

    Logging and error tracking: Implement a logging system to record 
    events, variable values, and error messages during gameplay. This 
    can help you identify patterns or reproduce errors more easily.

    Unit testing: Write unit tests for individual functions and 
    routines to ensure that they behave as expected in isolation. This 
    can help catch errors early and prevent them from affecting other 
    parts of your code.

    Community resources: If you encounter a particularly challenging 
    issue, don't hesitate to seek help from the Inform 6 community. 
    Online forums, tutorials, and documentation can provide valuable 
    insights and solutions.

By utilizing these debugging tools, techniques, and strategies 
effectively, you can identify and fix errors in your Inform 6 code 
efficiently, ensuring that your interactive fiction games are stable, 
polished, and enjoyable for your players.

Chapter 11.3: Testing Strategies for Interactive Fiction

Testing is a crucial phase in the development of any interactive 
fiction game. It helps ensure that your game is playable, enjoyable, 
and free from bugs and inconsistencies. Due to the open-ended nature 
of interactive fiction, testing requires specific strategies and 
approaches to effectively cover the wide range of possibilities and 
player choices.

This sub-chapter will offer a comprehensive exploration of testing 
strategies for interactive fiction in Inform 6, covering different 
testing phases, test case design, player feedback, and advanced 
techniques for ensuring the quality and polish of your interactive 
fiction games.

Testing Phases: A Structured Approach

It's helpful to break down testing into distinct phases:

    Unit testing: Test individual functions and routines in isolation 
    to ensure they behave as expected. This helps catch errors early 
    and prevents them from affecting other parts of your code.

    Integration testing: Test how different parts of your game work 
    together. This includes testing object interactions, room 
    connections, and the overall flow of the game.

    Functional testing: Test the core functionality of your game, 
    ensuring that players can complete puzzles, interact with 
    characters, and progress through the narrative.

    Usability testing: Observe players interacting with your game and 
    gather feedback on the user experience, puzzle design, and overall 
    game flow. This helps identify areas where the game might be 
    confusing or frustrating for players.

    Regression testing: After making changes to your code, re-run 
    previous tests to ensure that the changes haven't introduced new 
    bugs or regressions.

Test Case Design: Covering the Possibilities

Designing effective test cases is crucial for thorough testing. 
Consider the following when creating test cases:

    Positive and negative cases: Test both positive and negative cases 
    for actions and interactions. For example, test what happens when 
    the player uses the correct key on a door and what happens when 
    they use the wrong key.

    Edge cases: Test edge cases and boundary conditions to ensure your 
    code handles unexpected or unusual player input gracefully.

    Different paths and choices: If your game has branching narratives 
    or multiple solutions to puzzles, design test cases to cover 
    different paths and choices that the player might make.

    Order of actions: Test different orders in which the player might 
    perform actions, as this can sometimes reveal unexpected 
    interactions or bugs.

Player Feedback: Invaluable Insights

Gathering feedback from real players is invaluable for identifying 
issues and improving the overall player experience. Consider the 
following approaches:

