Chapter 11.4: Best Practices for Code Maintenance

Maintaining your Inform 6 code effectively is crucial for ensuring the 
long-term health and stability of your interactive fiction projects. 
As your codebase grows and evolves, adopting good maintenance 
practices will help you keep your code organized, readable, and easy 
to modify and extend.

This sub-chapter will offer a comprehensive exploration of best 
practices for code maintenance in Inform 6, covering code 
organization, commenting, version control, refactoring, and strategies 
for keeping your code clean and manageable as your project grows.

Code Organization: A Foundation for Maintainability

Organizing your code effectively is the cornerstone of good code 
maintenance. Here are some key strategies:

    Modularization: Divide your code into separate files based on 
    functionality or game regions. This improves organization and 
    allows for easier collaboration and targeted modifications.

    Use of Include: The Include directive allows you to incorporate 
    code from other files, promoting modularity and code reuse. Use it 
    to include libraries, extensions, and common code modules across 
    your project.

    Consistent naming conventions: Use consistent and meaningful names 
    for objects, routines, and variables to improve code readability 
    and make it easier to understand the purpose of different 
    elements.

    Indentation and spacing: Use indentation and spacing to visually 
    organize your code and highlight the logical structure. This makes 
    it easier to follow the flow of execution and identify specific 
    code blocks.

    Grouping related code: Group related routines and object 
    definitions together to improve navigation and understanding. This 
    helps you locate specific sections of code quickly and 
    efficiently.

Commenting: Explaining Your Code

Comments are essential for understanding the purpose and functionality 
of your code. Here are some key commenting practices:

    Clarity and conciseness: Write comments that are clear, concise, 
    and easy to understand. Avoid overly verbose explanations or 
    redundant information.

